\chapter{Introduction}

\section{Project Overview}

We propose a mobile application titled \textbf{PickMyDish – What Should I Eat Today?}.  
The idea originates from a common daily struggle: deciding what to cook or eat, especially when time, budget, or ingredients are limited.

The application recommends meals based on:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Ingredients the user already has,
    \item The user’s mood (e.g., healthy, lazy, hungry, energetic),
    \item The time available to prepare a meal.
\end{itemize}

The app provides:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Suggested recipes,
    \item Step-by-step instructions,
    \item Images of meals,
    \item Ability to save favorites.
\end{itemize}

The system is developed using Flutter and structured under a well-defined clean architecture.

\chapter{Application Architecture Overview}

\section{Main Application Setup}

The app is initialized in \texttt{Main.dart} using \texttt{MultiProvider}. It loads two core providers:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{UserProvider}: Manages authentication and profile data.
    \item \textbf{RecipeProvider}: Manages recipes and favorites.
\end{itemize}

The entry flow:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{SplashScreen} appears for 3 seconds.
    \item Navigates to \textbf{LoginScreen}.
\end{enumerate}

\section{State Management}

The application uses the \textbf{Provider} pattern for efficient state handling.

\subsection{UserProvider Manages:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Current user
    \item Profile data
    \item Preferences
\end{itemize}

\subsection{RecipeProvider Manages:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Recipe catalog
    \item Favorites
    \item Filtering logic
\end{itemize}

\section{Navigation Flow}

Users navigate through:

\begin{itemize}
    \item SplashScreen
    \item LoginScreen / RegisterScreen
    \item HomeScreen
    \item RecipesScreen
    \item FavoritesScreen
    \item ProfileScreen
    \item RecipeUploadScreen
\end{itemize}

